The '''Congress of Black Writers and Artists''' ([[French language|French]]: ''Congrès des écrivains et artistes noirs''; originally called the '''Congress of Negro Writers and Artists''') was a meeting of leading [[Black people|black]] [[intellectual]]s for the purpose of addressing the issues of [[colonialism]], [[slavery]], and ''[[Négritude]]''. The First Congress of Black Writers and Artists was organized by the [[Pan-Africanism|Pan-African]] quarterly cultural, political, and [[Literary magazine|literary review]] ''[[Présence Africaine]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of the African Diaspora: Origins, Experiences, and Culture|volume=1|author=[[Carole Boyce Davies]]|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|year=2008|page=767|isbn=1-85109-700-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P9ORpnGJh_IC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=&f=false}}</ref> It was held in [[Paris]] in September 1956.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Race, Culture, and the Intellectuals, 1940-1970|author=Richard H. King|publisher=[[Woodrow Wilson Center Press]]|year=2004|page=201|isbn=0-8018-8066-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kIZ2pAGyNYUC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=&f=false}}</ref> [[Ahmed Sékou Touré]] spoke at the Second Congress of Black Writers and Artists, which was held in [[Rome]] in 1959.<ref>{{Cite book|title=An African Voice: The Role of the Humanities in African Independence|author=Robert William July|publisher=[[Duke University Press]]|year=1987|page=24|isbn=0-8223-0769-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qF-QpNA2QqYC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=&f=false}}</ref>
